    <title>Introduction to JavaScript</title>
</head>
<body>

    <h1>Introduction to JavaScript</h1>

    <p>JavaScript has a myriad of capabilities, as demonstrated by the following examples:</p>

    <h2>Modifying HTML Content with JavaScript</h2>
    <p>Through methods like getElementById(), JavaScript can identify HTML elements and adjust their content:</p>

    <pre>
        Example:

        document.getElementById('example').innerHTML = 'Hi, JavaScript';
    </pre> 

    <p>Note that both single and double quotes are acceptable in JavaScript.</p>

    <h2>Altering HTML Attribute Values</h2>
    <p>Attributes of HTML tags, such as the src attribute of an <img> tag, can be changed with JavaScript.</p>

    <h2>Changing HTML Styles</h2>
    <p>HTML element styles can also be modified, like so:</p>

    <pre>
        Example:

        document.getElementById('example').style.fontSize = '25px';
    </pre> 

    <h2>Toggling HTML Element Visibility</h2>
    <p>To hide or show HTML elements, the display style can be adjusted:</p>

    <pre>
        Examples:

        document.getElementById('example').style.display = 'none'; // to hide
        document.getElementById('example').style.display = 'block'; // to show
    </pre> 

    <h2>Interesting JavaScript Facts</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Even though their names are similar, JavaScript and Java are distinct languages.</li>
        <li>JavaScript was created by Brendan Eich in 1995 and became an ECMA standard in 1997.</li>
        <li>The official standard name is ECMA-262, and the language's official title is ECMAScript.</li>
    </ul>
</body>
</html>